Fig. 4
 illustrated the biological activity of N–CDs as a ligand against Escherichia coli PDB (7AB4), Helicobacter pylori PDB (5Y2D), Micrococcus luteus PDB (4EWP) and Staphylococcus aureus PDB (7BGD) as a receptor. The N–CDs showed good binding with protein with short bond length 1.26, 3.02, 2.33 and 2.45 A° for Escherichia coli, Helicobacter pylori, Micrococcus luteus and Staphylococcus aureus, respectively. This finding is consistent with experimental studies on the material's antimicrobial properties. Shorter bond lengths between the ligand and the protein result in a more reactive ligand. This increased reactivity enables the ligand to form a stronger bond (chelate) with the protein, potentially impairing its function and killing the microbe (See Fig. 4a) [40] (See ​Fig. 5
).
